# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-sagemaker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] SageMaker enables developers to operate at a number of different levels of abstraction when training and deploying machine learning models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] At its highest level of abstraction, SageMaker provides pre-trained ML models that can be deployed as-is.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] It offers a number of built-in ML algorithms that developers can train on their own data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] The platform features managed instances of TensorFlow and Apache MXNet, where developers can create their own ML algorithms from scratch.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] A developer may also connect their SageMaker-enabled ML models to other AWS services, such as the Amazon DynamoDB database for structured data storage, AWS Batch for offline batch processing, or Amazon Kinesis for real-time processing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] Various interfaces are available for developers to interact with SageMaker.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] A web API may remotely control a SageMaker server instance.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] While the web API is agnostic to the programming language used by the developer, Amazon provides SageMaker API bindings for a number of languages, including Python, JavaScript, Ruby, Java, and Go.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] SageMaker Python SDK is accessible through Anaconda's community-led conda-forge channel.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] SageMaker also provides managed Jupyter Notebook instances for interactively programming SageMaker and other applications.
[src:aws-sagemaker/amazon-sagemaker] In December 2025, new serverless customization in SageMaker AI was announced to interface with AI models like Amazon Nova, Llama, Qwen, DeepSeek and GPT-OSS.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:aws-sagemaker/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In machine learning, **hyperparameter optimization** or tuning is the problem of choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A hyperparameter is a parameter whose value is used to control the learning process, which must be configured before the process starts.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperparameter optimization determines the set of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on a given data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] The objective function takes a set of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Cross-validation is often used to estimate this generalization performance, and therefore choose the set of values for hyperparameters that maximize it.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] The traditional method for hyperparameter optimization has been *grid search*, or a *parameter sweep*, which is simply an exhaustive searching through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space of a learning algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A grid search algorithm must be guided by some performance metric, typically measured by cross-validation on the training set or evaluation on a hold-out validation set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Since the parameter space of a machine learner may include real-valued or unbounded value spaces for certain parameters, manually set bounds and discretization may be necessary before applying grid search.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] For example, a typical soft-margin SVM classifier equipped with an RBF kernel has at least two hyperparameters that need to be tuned for good performance on unseen data: a regularization constant *C* and a kernel hyperparameter γ.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search then trains an SVM with each pair (*C*, γ) in the Cartesian product of these two sets and evaluates their performance on a held-out validation set (or by internal cross-validation on the training set, in which case multiple SVMs are trained per pair).
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Finally, the grid search algorithm outputs the settings that achieved the highest score in the validation procedure.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search suffers from the curse of dimensionality, but is often embarrassingly parallel because the hyperparameter settings it evaluates are typically independent of each other.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search replaces the exhaustive enumeration of all combinations by selecting them randomly.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be simply applied to the discrete setting described above, but also generalizes to continuous and mixed spaces.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A benefit over grid search is that random search can explore many more values than grid search could for continuous hyperparameters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] It can outperform Grid search, especially when only a small number of hyperparameters affects the final performance of the machine learning algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In this case, the optimization problem is said to have a low intrinsic dimensionality.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search is also embarrassingly parallel, and additionally allows the inclusion of prior knowledge by specifying the distribution from which to sample.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Despite its simplicity, random search remains one of the important base-lines against which to compare the performance of new hyperparameter optimization methods.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Bayesian optimization is a global optimization method for noisy black-box functions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Applied to hyperparameter optimization, Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic model of the function mapping from hyperparameter values to the objective evaluated on a validation set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] By iteratively evaluating a promising hyperparameter configuration based on the current model, and then updating it, Bayesian optimization aims to gather observations revealing as much information as possible about this function and, in particular, the location of the optimum.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] It tries to balance exploration (hyperparameters for which the outcome is most uncertain) and exploitation (hyperparameters expected close to the optimum).
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In practice, Bayesian optimization has been shown to obtain better results in fewer evaluations compared to grid search and random search, due to the ability to reason about the quality of experiments before they are run.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] For specific learning algorithms, it is possible to compute the gradient with respect to hyperparameters and then optimize the hyperparameters using gradient descent.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] The first usage of these techniques was focused on neural networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Since then, these methods have been extended to other models such as support vector machines or logistic regression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A different approach in order to obtain a gradient with respect to hyperparameters consists in differentiating the steps of an iterative optimization algorithm using automatic differentiation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A more recent work along this direction uses the implicit function theorem to calculate hypergradients and proposes a stable approximation of the inverse Hessian.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] The method scales to millions of hyperparameters and requires constant memory.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In a different approach, a hypernetwork is trained to approximate the best response function.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] One of the advantages of this method is that it can handle discrete hyperparameters as well.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Self-tuning networks offer a memory efficient version of this approach by choosing a compact representation for the hypernetwork.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Apart from hypernetwork approaches, gradient-based methods can be used to optimize discrete hyperparameters also by adopting a continuous relaxation of the parameters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Such methods have been extensively used for the optimization of architecture hyperparameters in neural architecture search.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization is a methodology for the global optimization of noisy black-box functions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In hyperparameter optimization, evolutionary optimization uses evolutionary algorithms to search the space of hyperparameters for a given algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Repeat steps 2-4 until satisfactory algorithm performance is reached or is no longer improving.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization has been used in hyperparameter optimization for statistical machine learning algorithms, automated machine learning, typical neural network and deep neural network architecture search, as well as training of the weights in deep neural networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Population Based Training (PBT) learns both hyperparameter values and network weights.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Multiple learning processes operate independently, using different hyperparameters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] As with evolutionary methods, poorly performing models are iteratively replaced with models that adopt modified hyperparameter values and weights based on the better performers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] This replacement model warm starting is the primary differentiator between PBT and other evolutionary methods.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT thus allows the hyperparameters to evolve and eliminates the need for manual hypertuning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] The process makes no assumptions regarding model architecture, loss functions or training procedures.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT and its variants are adaptive methods: they update hyperparameters during the training of the models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] On the contrary, non-adaptive methods have the sub-optimal strategy to assign a constant set of hyperparameters for the whole training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] A class of early stopping-based hyperparameter optimization algorithms is purpose-built for large search spaces of continuous and discrete hyperparameters, particularly when the computational cost to evaluate the performance of a set of hyperparameters is high.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Irace implements the iterated racing algorithm, that focuses the search around the most promising configurations, using statistical tests to discard the ones that perform poorly.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Another early stopping hyperparameter optimization algorithm is successive halving (SHA), which begins as a random search but periodically prunes low-performing models, thereby focusing computational resources on more promising models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Asynchronous successive halving (ASHA) further improves upon SHA's resource utilization profile by removing the need to synchronously evaluate and prune low-performing models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperband is a higher level early stopping-based algorithm that invokes SHA or ASHA multiple times with varying levels of pruning aggressiveness, in order to be more widely applicable and with fewer required inputs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] RBF and spectral approaches have also been developed.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] When hyperparameter optimization is done, the set of hyperparameters are often fitted on a training set and selected based on the generalization performance, or score, of a validation set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] However, this procedure is at risk of overfitting the hyperparameters to the validation set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] Therefore, the generalization performance score of the validation set (which can be several sets in the case of a cross-validation procedure) cannot be used to simultaneously estimate the generalization performance of the final model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] In order to do so, the generalization performance has to be evaluated on a set independent (which has no intersection) of the set (or sets) used for the optimization of the hyperparameters, otherwise the performance might give a value which is too optimistic (too large).
[src:aws-sagemaker/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be done on a second test set, or through an outer cross-validation procedure called nested cross-validation, which allows an unbiased estimation of the generalization performance of the model, taking into account the bias due to the hyperparameter optimization.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:aws-sagemaker/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] The word is a compound of "machine learning" and the continuous delivery practice (CI/CD) of DevOps in the software field.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Machine learning models are tested and developed in isolated experimental systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] When an algorithm is ready to be launched, MLOps is practiced between data scientists, DevOps, and machine learning engineers to transition the algorithm to production systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Similar to DevOps or DataOps approaches, MLOps seeks to increase automation and improve the quality of production models, while also focusing on business and regulatory requirements.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] While MLOps started as a set of best practices, it is slowly evolving into an independent approach to ML lifecycle management.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] MLOps applies to the entire lifecycle - from integrating with model generation (software development lifecycle, continuous integration/continuous delivery), orchestration, and deployment, to health, diagnostics, governance, and business metrics.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] MLOps is a paradigm, including aspects like best practices, sets of concepts, as well as a development culture when it comes to the end-to-end conceptualization, implementation, monitoring, deployment, and scalability of machine learning products.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Most of all, it is an engineering practice that leverages three contributing disciplines: machine learning, software engineering (especially DevOps), and data engineering.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] MLOps is aimed at productionizing machine learning systems by bridging the gap between development (Dev) and operations (Ops).
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Interest in operationalizing machine learning systems began to grow in the mid-2010s as ML projects started moving from experimentation to production use.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] The challenges associated with sustaining such systems were highlighted in a 2015 paper.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] The predicted growth in machine learning included an estimated doubling of ML pilots and implementations from 2017 to 2018, and again from 2018 to 2020.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Reports show a majority (up to 88%) of corporate machine learning initiatives are struggling to move beyond test stages.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] However, those organizations that actually put machine learning into production saw a 3–15% profit margin increases.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] The MLOps market size was USD 2,191.8 Million in 2024, and is projected to be USD 16,613.4 Million in 2030.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Machine Learning systems can be categorized in eight different categories: data collection, data processing, feature engineering, data labeling, model design, model training and optimization, endpoint deployment, and endpoint monitoring.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Each step in the machine learning lifecycle is built in its own system, but requires interconnection.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] These are the minimum systems that enterprises need to scale machine learning within their organization.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] A standard practice, such as MLOps, takes into account each of the aforementioned areas, which can help enterprises optimize workflows and avoid issues during implementation.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] Vendors such as Adaptive ML deliver commercial reinforcement learning operations (RLOps) and MLOps-infrastructure, targeting organizations deploying large language models in production.
[src:aws-sagemaker/mlops] A common architecture of an MLOps system would include data science platforms where models are constructed and the analytical engines where computations are performed, with the MLOps tool orchestrating the movement of machine learning models, data and outcomes between the systems.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] A **notebook interface** or **computational notebook** is a virtual notebook environment used for literate programming, a method of writing computer programs.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Some notebooks are WYSIWYG environments including executable calculations embedded in formatted documents; others separate calculations and text into separate sections.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Notebooks share some goals and features with spreadsheets and word processors but go beyond their limited data models.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Modular notebooks may connect to a variety of computational back ends, called "kernels".
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Notebook interfaces are widely used for statistics, data science, machine learning, and computer algebra.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] VisiCalc, the first spreadsheet for personal computers, was published in 1979.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Its idea of visual calculations is still widely used today but limited to documents that fit into a table.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Research on WYSIWYG mathematical systems supporting mixed text and calculations with a document metaphor begin to be published in 1987: Ron Avitzur's *Milo*, William Schelter's *INFOR*, Xerox PARC's *Tioga* and *CaminoReal*.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] The earliest commercial system using the document metaphor was *MathCAD*, which also came out in 1987.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] *Wolfram Mathematica* 1.0 followed in 1988.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] As the notebook interface increased in popularity over the next two decades, notebooks for various computational back ends ("kernels") have been introduced, including MATLAB, Python, Julia, R, Scala, Elixir, SQL, and others.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] The variety of notebook interface has since been extended and new forms are still evolving.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Notebooks are traditionally used in the sciences as electronic lab notebooks to document research procedures, data, calculations, and findings.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Notebooks track methodology to make it easier to reproduce results and calculations with different data sets.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] In education, the notebook interface provides a digital learning environment, particularly for the teaching of computational thinking.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Their utility for combining text with code makes them unique in the realm of education.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Digital notebooks are sometimes used for presentations as an alternative to PowerPoint and other presentation software, as they allow for the execution of code inside the notebook environment.
[src:aws-sagemaker/notebook-interface] Due to their ability to display data visually and retrieve data from different sources by modifying code, notebooks are also entering the realm of business intelligence software.
